               <desc>
                  <p type="site-data">
                     The Zhengding Tianning Monastery (正定天宁寺) is located in Zhengding County, Hebei Province and is recognized as a National Key Cultural Relic Protection Unit (Quanguo Zhongdian Wenwu Baohu Danwei 全国重点文物保护单位). 
                     Established during the Tang Dynasty under Emperor Yizong in the Xiantong era (860–874), the monastery was originally known as Dazang Courtyard (Dazang Yuan 大藏院). Historically, it was one of the most prominent Buddhist sites in Zhengding, featuring a grand and meticulously planned layout. Key structures, including an ornate archway, multiple gates, the Hall of Heavenly Kings (Tianwang Dian 天王殿), front and rear halls, and the iconic Lingxiao Pagoda (Lingxiao Ta 凌霄塔), were arranged along a central north-south axis, reflecting the architectural and spiritual principles of the era (Li 48). 
                     Although much of the original complex was lost due to destruction during subsequent periods, the remnants of Tianning Monastery retain profound historical and cultural value. The Mountain Gate (Shanmen 山门) serves as the entrance, showcasing intricate craftsmanship and acting as a symbolic threshold to the sacred site. Beyond the gate, traces of the foundational halls remain, offering a glimpse into the grandeur and symmetry of the original design. These remnants underscore the monastery’s historical role as both a spiritual hub and an architectural landmark in northern China. 
                     Tianning Monastery has weathered centuries of change, enduring periods of decline and reconstruction. It remains an essential part of Zhengding’s heritage, reflecting the region’s deep Buddhist traditions and historical significance.   
                  </p>
